\par \u10095? \cf4\f1 Yes \emdash  for **Sloyd specifically**, start with **text-to-3D first**. Sloyd officially supports both **text-to-3D** and **image-to-3D**, and says text prompts alone can generate textured, export-ready\cf1\f0 
\par \cf4   models, while image-to-3D is for uploaded photos, sketches, or reference images. ([Sloyd][1])\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   For your game, I\rquote d use this rule:\cf1\f0 
\par 
\par \cf4   **Use Sloyd text-to-3D by default** for standard props and modular pieces.\cf1 
\par \cf4   **Use image-to-3D only when you need a very specific silhouette or style reference** that text prompts keep missing. ([Sloyd][1])\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   I would **not** make a DALL\'b7E image first for every asset. That adds an extra step and can drift away from \ldblquote game-ready\rdblquote  structure. Sloyd already has direct text generation plus procedural/template\cf1\f0 
\par \cf4   controls intended for game assets, which is usually the cleaner path. Sloyd also emphasizes customizable procedural generators and export-ready formats like GLB/FBX/OBJ. ([Sloyd][1])\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   A better workflow is:\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4   * **Text \u8594? Sloyd** for most assets\cf1 
\par \cf4\f1   * **DALL\'b7E / GPT Image \f0\u8594? Sloyd image-to-3D** only for hero props, unique faction pieces, or when you want to lock a visual direction first\cf1 
\par \cf4   * **Then Blender cleanup** either way\cf1 
\par 
\par \cf4\f1   Also, OpenAI\rquote s image docs say newer image generation is available via GPT Image, while DALL\'b7E 3 remains a text-to-image generation model; so for making references, an image model is fine, but it should\cf1\f0 
\par \cf4   be a selective preproduction tool, not your default 3D pipeline. ([OpenAI Developers][2])\cf1 
\par 
